Retrieved from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data?resource=download

Breast Cancer Wisconsin Data Classification Project¶

About The Dataset (info from Kaggle's page)¶

Features are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image. n the 3-dimensional space is that described in: [K. P. Bennett and O. L. Mangasarian: "Robust Linear Programming Discrimination of Two Linearly Inseparable Sets", Optimization Methods and Software 1, 1992, 23-34].

This database is also available through the UW CS ftp server: ftp ftp.cs.wisc.edu cd math-prog/cpo-dataset/machine-learn/WDBC/

Also can be found on UCI Machine Learning Repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+%28Diagnostic%29

FEATURES Information:

  1. ID number
  2. Diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign) 3-32)

Ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus:

  1. radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
  2. texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
  3. perimeter
  4. area
  5. smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
  6. compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)
  7. concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
  8. concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
  9. symmetry
  10. fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

The mean, standard error and "worst" or largest (mean of the three largest values) of these features were computed for each image, resulting in 30 features. For instance, field 3 is Mean Radius, field 13 is Radius SE, field 23 is Worst Radius.

NOTE: FOR THIS PROJECT ONLY THE FIRST 12 COLUMNS WILL BE KEPT, THE "STANDARD_ERROR", AND "WORST" FEATURES WILL BE DROPPED.

All feature values are recoded with four significant digits.

Missing attribute values: none

Class distribution: 357 benign, 212 malignant

Main objectives¶

  1. Do EDA (the data wrangling is done by default)
  2. Transform/Standardize data (preprocessing)
  3. Train 3 classification models
  4. Finally, predict whether the cancer is benign or malignant

In [ ]:
def visualize_feature_importance(importance_array):
    # Sort the array based on mean value
    sorted_idx = importance_array.importances_mean.argsort()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    fig.set_figwidth(14)
    fig.set_figheight(8)
    fig.tight_layout()
    ax.boxplot(importance_array.importances[sorted_idx].T,
               vert=False, labels=X_train_scaled_df.columns[sorted_idx])
    ax.set_title("Permutation Importances (train set)")
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
visualize_feature_importance(feature_importances)

Precision, Recall, F1, AUC, scores comparison¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score, precision_recall_fscore_support, confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, precision_score, recall_score, roc_auc_score
In [ ]:
models_scores = {}
models_list = [RF_best,Log_best,KNN_best]
model_name = ["RandomForest","LogisticRegression", "KNNeigbors"]
In [ ]:
for model,label in zip(models_list,model_name):
    pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled_df)
    precision, recall, f1, support = precision_recall_fscore_support(y_test, pred, beta=1, average='binary')
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, pred)
    models_scores[label] = [precision, recall, f1,auc]
In [ ]:
scores_df = pd.DataFrame(models_scores)

scores_df = scores_df.T
scores_df.columns = ["precision","recall","f1","auc"]

It can be appreciated from the scores dataframe above that the model with the highest precision is the Logistic Regression, the highest recall goes to the Random Forest, the highest f1 corresponds to Logistic Regression, and finally the highest auc score model is the Logistic Regression¶

Although all models have considerably high scores in all of the metrics I believe that the model to be considered is the Logistic Regression model with L1 penalty (Lasso) not only because it has most of the high scores of the metrics, but because it's also a pretty simple model to train and it doesn't require much computation power to train and predict.¶

Key Findings¶

  1. EDA process was short at most since the data wrangling process had taken place beforehand. However, the EDA ensured that the data had no duplicates, there were no missing values, and a logarithmic transformation was performed on the Feature columns (only on positively skewed values with a score higher than 0.7) for data normalization.

  2. Data standardization helped train the models, more specifically those that were trained with Regularization techniques such as Lasso o Ridge.

  3. Data split stratification had to be done since the Target classes was of about 2:1 (Benign : Malicious), this is probably not a very skewed behavior, but it's good practice to secure the ratios.

  4. The Permutation Importance scores demonstrated that out of the 11 features that were used to train the models the most important ones were 'concave points_mean', 'texture_mean', and 'concavity_mean'.

  5. The Partial Dependency Display plots suggest that tumors with more concave points, higher concavity, and rougher textures are more likely to be classified as malignant. This aligns with medical knowledge, as malignant tumors often have more irregular shapes and textures compared to benign ones.

  6. All models' metrics had a score higher than 0.85 on the Unseen Data, but due to the different complexities of the models (RandomForest & KNN) the best model to use moving forward probably is the Logistic Regression.

Possible flaws in the model and a plan of action moving forward¶

  1. Overfitting the data: although the RandomForest is the least correlated model for the Tree Classifiers, it could be overfit if the number of leaves or the depth of the tree wasn't correctly tuned. Also, it might be a good idea to try a classifier different from KNN if down the road the dataset got larger.

  2. The plan moving forward could be to investigate model performance across different patient demographics, compare performance across different models (e.g. SVM, neural networks).
